# Trivy vulnerability ignore list
# Each entry must have a justification comment.

# CVE-2026-33671 — picomatch ≤4.0.3 ReDoS (HIGH)
# Affected path in node:24-alpine:
#   /usr/local/lib/node_modules/npm/node_modules/tinyglobby/node_modules/picomatch
# This is bundled inside npm's OWN internal CLI tooling (tinyglobby), not in
# the application runtime code. The project's own picomatch is already at
# 4.0.4 (fixed). The upstream npm@11.12.1 (latest as of 2026-04-18) still
# bundles the older version; no fix is available in a newer npm release yet.
# Risk: zero — the vulnerable code path is only reachable via npm CLI internals,
# never executed by the MCP server at runtime.
CVE-2026-33671

# CVE-2026-53550 — js-yaml ≤4.1.1 quadratic-complexity DoS via merge key aliases (Moderate, CVSS 5.3)
# Affected path in Docker image:
#   /app/node_modules/gray-matter/node_modules/js-yaml@3.14.2
# gray-matter@4.0.3 bundles its own js-yaml@3.14.2 for YAML front-matter parsing.
# js-yaml 4.2.0 (fixed) is present at the top-level, but gray-matter uses its own
# pinned copy and does not share it.
# Fix is not available in the 3.x branch; upgrading gray-matter would require a
# breaking major version change (gray-matter@2.0.1) that removes features in use.
# Risk: negligible — gray-matter is used exclusively to parse the project's own
# skill/instruction YAML files bundled at build time, never user-supplied YAML input.
# The DoS vector requires a crafted document with deeply nested merge aliases, which
# cannot be injected by external callers in this deployment.
CVE-2026-53550
